<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / Whitehall faces strike vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADERS of the NUCPS Civil Service union are to ballot their 110,000 members
on industrial action, including strikes, over a proposed radical shake-up of
Whitehall pay.
The government has offered a 4.45 per cent cost-of-living award, plus
performance-related pay and regrading said to be worth 0.3 per cent. Rules
governing Civil Service pay involve a minimum settlement of 4.5 per cent
this year.
The Treasury yesterday improved its offer from 4.1 per cent after the NUCPS
indicated it would reject it. Mr Leslie Christie, NUCPS general secretary,
said: 'My national executive council is not prepared to sign an agreement
which signals the end of national bargaining and removes the expectation of
annual pay increments as of right.'
The CPSA union, which represents 125,000 civil servants in clerical grades,
is understood to be expecting a cost-of-living award of less than 4 per
cent, plus performance pay.
Earlier this year the two unions indicated that they would seek compensation
for changes in pay bargaining structures that are demanded by the Treasury.
The changes are aimed at extending performance-related pay and increasing
the scope for government departments to opt out of centralised pay
bargaining.
</TEXT>
