FT  01 MAY 92 / Contact lens industry probed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Monopolies and Mergers Commission is to investigate the cost of contact
lens solutions following complaints, Jane Fuller writes.
The Office of Fair Trading referred the matter to the MMC yesterday on price
and competition issues after a preliminary investigation of the Pounds 40m
UK market for contact lens solutions was triggered by complaints from the
public.
The OFT said suppliers of contact lens solutions 'may be enjoying high rates
of return, suggesting that price competition in this market is not as
effective as it might be'.
It said the leading suppliers - Allergan UK, part of a US group, and Ciba
Vision UK, a subsidiary of Ciba-Geigy of Switzerland - might each have 25
per cent of the market.
A report published last September in Which?, the Consumers' Association
magazine, suggested that while a pair of contact lenses might cost about
Pounds 110, the annual bill for lens-care products could be Pounds 123 to
Pounds 197 for soft lenses and Pounds 89 to Pounds 147 for the gas-permeable
type.
According to the Association of Contact Lens Manufacturers, more than 1.5m
people in the UK wear contact lenses, representing about 5 per cent of those
who need some form of correction to their eyesight.
