<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / Lloyd's Names may win help to ease losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S of London yesterday announced that it is considering measures to
help Names hit by recent losses and said that the first moves to introduce
reforms recommended earlier this year by the Rowland task force had been
taken.
Mr Alan Lord, chief executive, said the Council, the insurance market's
governing body, had 'discussed in broad outline' the possibility of
providing a measure of financial assistance to Names facing severe
underwriting losses.
Several hundred Names - individuals whose assets support underwriting at
Lloyd's - face acute financial problems as a result of losses run up by
catastrophe reinsurance syndicates in 1989 and 1990.
Mr Lord said: 'Much further work is required on this complex matter before
we can establish the feasibility of any scheme in detail. The whole question
is being pushed ahead as rapidly as possible.' He added, however, that a
'successful outcome' could not be guaranteed.
Names would be consulted 'in the normal way', added Mr Lord, who said a
ballot or referendum of the membership of Lloyd's was possible.
Mr Lord also said Lloyd's was making 'considerable progress' on implementing
recommendations relating to Mapas - the unit-trust-type arrangements which
allow Names to spread their participation in syndicates more widely across
the market and reduce risk - as suggested by the Rowland task force when it
reported in January.
Lloyd's is understood to be negotiating with regulatory and tax authorities
about the impact of these changes.
The council has agreed to implement a change to the agency agreement, which
governs the relationship between Names and their agents.
The modified agency agreement includes a new 'deficit clause' which allows
Names to offset the profit commission paid to agents against losses made in
the previous two years, rather than one year as at present.
Another aspect of the scheme would eventually allow for compulsory
arbitration of all disputes between Names and their agents.
