FT  01 MAY 92 / Cabinet sets emissions timetable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday set a new timetable for reducing the UK's emissions
of greenhouse gases. It declared its aim of reducing emissions of carbon
dioxide to 1990 levels by the year 2000, rather 2005, the previous target.
The cabinet said the new target was demanding and it would press ahead with
reducing emissions on condition that other countries take similar action.
'It is hoped that all industrialised countries can make a similar commitment
at the final session of the Climate Change Convention negotiations currently
taking place in New York.' the statement said.
However environmental groups were quick to point out that, without specific
policies, targets to reduce emissions are meaningless.
Mr Andrew Warren, director of the Association for the Conservation of
Energy, said: 'In 1990 the government said it would take 15 years to
stabilise emissions. But since then, carbon dioxide emissions in the UK have
risen by 2 per cent even while GDP has fallen. Investment in energy
conservation has dropped by 28 per cent.'
Meanwhile, the cross-party House of Lords European Communities committee has
urged the government to oppose the carbon/energy tax proposed by the
European Commission.
In a report published today, the committee argues that the proposed tax  -
initially Dollars 3 per barrel of oil equivalent in 1993 and rising by
Dollars 1 a year to a maximum of Dollars 10 by 2000 - would encourage
switching to natural gas and nuclear energy at the expense of coal and oil.
While it did not rule out the use of fiscal instruments to limit emissions
of carbon dioxide, the committee stressed the proposed tax was 'a unilateral
response to a global problem'.
Compliance with a government proposal to speed up reduction of carbon
dioxide emissions is likely to increase costs for both the motor industry
and motorists, the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders said
yesterday.
</TEXT>
