<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / Borrie urges end to CPS restriction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bar's attempts to defend its 200-year monopoly on advocacy in the higher
courts suffered a setback yesterday when Sir Gordon Borrie, director-general
of fair trading, said that a restriction on barristers employed by the Crown
Prosecution Service appearing as advocates in the Crown Court was
anti-competitive and should be removed.
In his advice to the lord chancellor on wider rights of audience for
barristers in the employed sector, Sir Gordon says a rule in the Bar's Code
of Conduct 'has the effect of significantly restricting competition for
supplying the Crown with prosecution advocacy services in the higher
courts.'
There was no case on competition grounds for retaining the restriction on
CPS barristers, 'even on the extreme assumption of all prosecution work
being undertaken in the employed sector,' he said.
The rule also had an anti-competitive effect on advocacy in the civil courts
by preventing barristers who work in central and local government and in
commerce, finance and industry from representing their employers in the
higher courts, but the effect was not significant, he said.
Sir Gordon's view is only one of those which must be considered by the lord
chancellor before he makes his mind up about who should be able to present
cases in the higher courts, but his advice is bound to carry some weight
with a government committed to competition and to stamping out restrictive
practices.
The Bar played down the significance of Sir Gordon's advice. Mr Gareth
Williams QC, chairman of the Bar, said Sir Gordon had been 'judging the
restriction strictly against competition criteria which is a very small part
of the argument and by no means the most important'.
The CPS said yesterday it was delighted by Sir Gordon's recommendation.
'This adds further weight to our argument that the continued denial of
rights of audience in the higher courts for Crown Prosecutors is
unacceptable,' it said. The Law Society also welcomed the advice. 'The same
arguments must clearly apply to employed solicitors,' Mr Philip Ely, society
president, said.
</TEXT>
