<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / Five deny insider dealing charges: Biggest British
prosecution sees 'network of friends' accused of knowingly misusing
information on bids
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A 'NETWORK of friends' employed by financial institutions used
price-sensitive inside information about imminent takeover bids to make
profits for themselves or clients, it was alleged at the Old Bailey
yesterday.
In the case, the biggest UK insider dealing prosecution, five people deny
charges under the 1985 Company Securities (Insider Dealing) Act.
Mr David Gray, a former broker with Morgan Grenfell Securities, faces two
charges of unlawfully communicating unpublished price-sensitive information
to another person, two of dealing on the basis of such information and one
of counselling or procuring another person to deal.
Mr William Liggins, a former Lazards fund manager, is accused of two
offences of dealing and one of communicating.
Miss Catherine Rowlands, who was employed in the corporate finance
department at Samuel Montagu, is charged with three offences of
communicating information. Mr Mark Riding, former fund manager with the
Co-operative Insurance Society in Manchester, faces three dealing charges.
Mr Keith Tondeur, formerly UK head of principal trading and sales with
Banque Paribas, faces one dealing charge.
The alleged offences relate to three takeover bids in 1988. Hawthorn Leslie
Group, the USM-quoted cellular phone company, acquired ECT Cellular and
London Car Telephones; Australian company Goodman Fielder Wattie made a bid,
which lapsed, for UK foods group Ranks Hovis McDougall; and Mecca Leisure
acquired Pleasurama, the leisure group.
Mr Peter Clarke, prosecuting for the Department of Trade and Industry, said
some of the defendants had passed information to others, who had acted on it
by dealing in shares or by passing it on and advising other people to deal.
Profits had ranged from just Pounds 1,200 to Pounds 20,000, but the case
concerned a principle about the use of inside information.
Mr Clarke said the jury would hear several hours of recorded telephone
conversations between Mr Gray and other defendants peppered with references
to being unable to talk freely, or arrangements to see or speak to each
other out of office hours.
Mr Clarke said the five's motives had included personal greed, winning the
respect of others, repaying favours and enhancing their own reputations. But
whatever their motives, 'the fact is that it was illegal and they all knew
it'.
That was shown by the telephone conversations. The speed with which some
defendants acted after receiving information showed their knowledge of the
impropriety of what they were doing.
Mr Clarke said Mr Gray and Mr Liggins would be heard on the tapes discussing
what they had heard from an account director with Binns Cornwall, a
financial public relations company retained by Hawthorn Leslie for its bids.
Miss Rowlands had been the source of the inside information about RHM and
Pleasurama, Mr Clarke alleged. Samuel Montagu had been GFW's main adviser
and Mr Gray would be heard on the tapes referring to 'Wickets', Samuel
Montagu's codename for GFW, in a conversation with Miss Rowlands. Samuel
Montagu had also acted for Mecca. Miss Rowlands had not been part of that
team but had learned of the pending deal from a colleague who had warned her
not to buy Pleasurama shares, Mr Clarke said.
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
