<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / Hopes of recovery are raised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOPES that the economy might be recovering from recession were raised
yesterday by an indication that manufacturing output grew for the third
successive month in April.
The purchasing managers index, which measures demand trends among big
corporate and public-sector buyers, rose to 55.1 per cent last month, from
54.1 per cent in March. It was the highest level since the survey began in
July.
'This latest rise suggests strongly that significant growth is under way in
the manufacturing sector of British industry,' said the Institute of
Purchasing and Supply, which carries out the survey.
Earlier this month, the Central Statistical Office released figures showing
that manufacturing output increased by 1.1 per cent in February.
The survey, which covers 250 purchasing managers responsible for Pounds
250bn of corporate money each year, found that the new-orders index fell
slightly last month, although it remained above the 50 per cent level. The
prices index rose on the month.
