<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / World Trade News: Riots sharpen Clinton Bush rivalry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush and Governor Bill Clinton, each conscious that the
other's campaign was watching closely, walked a fine, and moveable, line
yesterday in reacting to the riots in Los Angeles.
Mr Bush began the day urging calm and expressing his own deep anguish. A
noontime televised statement touched all bases, but it led off with what he
called 'frustration over a verdict' and emphasised that the Justice
Department would continue a criminal investigation of the police violence
case in Los Angeles.
By mid-afternoon, the president was in Columbus, Ohio, and there had been a
discernible shift in emphasis. He spoke of his 'revulsion and pain' at the
street violence, of 'mob brutality' that was 'sickeningly sad'.
He did not mention federal action against the acquitted police offers, but
said: 'I will keep telling the country that we must stand up against
lawlessness and crime wherever it happens .. and what happened last night
was purely criminal.'
At the same time his spokesman, Marlin Fitzwater, was telling the travelling
press that Mr Clinton's reactions throughout the day had been politically
conditioned and were worthy of 'slippery Willie.' He added that the
president of the United States would never second guess the verdict of an
American jury.
The Democrat's first reaction on Tuesday night had been to condemn the trial
verdict. Yesterday morning he said the riots had been a reflection of
society's failure, a lack of faith in a system that was no longer
responsive. But he, too, urged an end to the violence.
When Mr Bush announced possible federal prosecution, Mr Clinton said that
was the right way to go. With Mr Bush emphasising his involvement in solving
the problem, and with a previously arranged trip to California on the
presidential schedule next week, Mr Clinton said he was contemplating going
to California to see if he could help.
At the end of the day, it almost seemed that both had reverted to political
type, the president talking up law and order, always a strong Republican
issue, Mr Clinton arguing the case for social healing, which he has tried to
make his issue this year, and for programmes to assist inner city
revitalisation.
Bill Schneider, the political expert, pointed out on TV that urban violence
tends to polarise American opinion, generally towards the right, where Mr
Bush sits. The US public seems to expect a strong response, which a centrist
like Mr Clinton may find hard to express.
On the other hand, shock at the acquittal of the police officers seems to
have been universal, cutting across racial divides. Failure to bring the
weight of federal prosecution against the four policemen following their
acquittal in the state courts would be widely, and unkindly, noticed.
Rev Jesse Jackson, the black activist, attacked the Los Angeles police
force, recalling its past history of violence before the Rodney King affair,
and recalling that its police chief, Daryl Gates, was close to the
president.
Mr Jackson himself, never shy of publicity but sensing the need for some
leadership, was as active as any yesterday. He conferred with William Barr,
the attorney general, and with Mr Clinton. He promised to go to Los Angeles.
He was constantly on television.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
