<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / World Trade News: Judgment day for City of Angels: An
eyewitness account of Los Angeles in turmoil
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BILL GIRDNER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SMELL of smoke and distant shouting was the signal that a violent
demonstration was in progress outside the headquarters of the Los Angeles
police department.
The court acquittal of four white policemen filmed on video brutally beating
a black motorist was only the latest spark to set an American city burning.
When the protesters came into view, people with their shirts off were
dancing up to the flames of a burning kiosk. The front doors of the police
station were smashed. The crowded chanted : 'No justice, no peace.' A black
cyclist stood watching the fire. 'I came for a demonstration, not a fight,'
said Robert Collins. His wife had resigned from the police force after
seeing too many beatings, he said.
Mr Collins was sympathetic with the demonstrators' rage, saying he had been
arrested repeatedly based on his skin colour.
Night workers stood watching at City Hall nearby as the crowd began to move.
When rocks and bottles were thrown, a policewoman shouted to her colleagues:
'Everybody inside.' She locked the main doors to City Hall and all garage
doors were quickly closed.
A short time later she let in two women reporters who had run from the
criminal court across the street. In a press room on the 14th floor of the
criminal court, they had smelt smoke and ran, in a panic, down 14 flights of
stairs.
In the lobby of the criminal court they found police officers who escorted
them out of the building. All the lobby windows had been smashed, and smoke
from burning shrubs filled the first few floors of the court house.
Safely inside City Hall, they watched as the turbulent crowd led by five
young men went down the street, smashed windows, overturned cars and set
them on fire. In driving to a hospital a mile south, the crowds's wake was
evident. Huge panes of windows had been broken out of banks and the Los
Angeles Times building, leaving venetian blinds and chairs askew.
Firefighters were spraying water on an overturned car, filling the canyon
between buildings with white smoke. A news kiosk had been overturned and
burnt to a cinder.
In the hospital waiting room a large black man in shorts waited patiently
with a bloody bandage around his calf. He had been shot. Another woman was
wheeled in, and she weakly handed her insurance papers up to the
receptionist. She said she had been shot in the foot.
A local resident, Mrs Delores Hill, said a liquor store where her husband
bought cigarettes had been looted and burned. The shopkeeper had become a
friend, she said. 'It's like a family,' said Mrs Hill. 'The neighbourhood
family has been wiped out.'
As looting went on unchecked in some areas, outnumbered police stood
helplessly. 'They're taking advantage of the situation to come and have a
shopping spree,' said a police sergeant who refused to give his name.
Many of the establishments looted belonged to Koreans, who have increasingly
come to dominate business in black neighbourhoods, fuelling resentment among
residents.
But blacks also suffered heavily. 'They've looted and burned my store,' said
Michael Stennis, owner of a fried chicken outlet. 'My family's been in this
area for 35 years. We're black. It's senseless.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
