FT  01 MAY 92 / International Company News: General Re shares tumble on weak
results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in General Reinsurance lost about 10 per cent of their value
yesterday morning, falling Dollars 8 1/2 to Dollars 79 7/8 , after the US
insurer reported a sharp deterioration in first quarter underwriting results
and warned that the rest of year would probably be 'unsatisfactory'.
The news came as American International Group, the large composite insurer,
also said it saw no pricing improvement in the domestic property-casualty
industry.
Its own shares slipped Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 83 1/2 , and the two
announcements caused shares across the industry to weaken. Aetna lost
Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 42 3/4 ; Cigna fell by Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 51
7/8 ; and Travelers lost Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 20 7/8 .
General Re, the largest reinsurance company in the US, reported a fall in
operating profits, from Dollars 135.1m to Dollars 116.5m. The figure is
struck before realised investment gains, which increased from Dollars 15.3m
to Dollars 30.3m, and an accounting change item, which added Dollars 61m.
After-tax profits, therefore, were Dollars 207.8m, against Dollars 150.4m.
The company said underwriting results had been 'very disappointing' - the
combined underwriting ratio for the property-casualty companies worsening
from 99.7 per cent a year ago to 105.4 per cent - and warned more bad news
was to come.
'Based on the first quarter results, the lead time required for our
initiatives to take effect and several major insurance industry losses which
have already occured in the second quarter, underwriting results are likely
to be unsatisfactory for the balance of the year,' said Mr Ronald Ferguson,
chairman.
Meanwhile, AIG reported first-quarter profits of Dollars 413.9m after tax,
up from Dollars 375.4m a year earlier. Pre-tax realised capital gains
amounted to Dollars 28m compared with Dollars 23.6m.
On the general insurance side, there was a tiny underwriting loss, compared
with a Dollars 24.8m profit a year earlier. But net investment income
increased by 9.2 per cent to Dollars 308.8m, taking operating profits to
Dollars 308.2m compared with Dollars 307.9m last time.
Operating profits from the life side increased by 16.1 per cent to Dollars
141.5m, while financial services contributed Dollars 62.4m (Dollars 47m).
The insurer said it had not seen 'any material change in the pricing
environment in the domestic property-casualty industry since the last
quarter' but noted that several specialty classes of business continued to
do well.
