<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 92 / Sizewell replica to aid nuclear training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FULL-SCALE replica of the future control room at Sizewell B, the
pressurised water reactor nuclear power station due to start up on the
Suffolk coast in 1994, opens today. It will be used to train Sizewell's
operators.
The replica is housed in Cliff Quay, a futuristic building next to a disused
power station on the River Orwell at Ipswich. It has been built by Nuclear
Electric, the state-owned operator of the nuclear power stations in England
and Wales.
The control room mimics Sizewell down to the carpet tiles. Its sophisticated
Marconi-designed software 'thinks it is a power station', according to
Nuclear Electric.
For the operators, the control room 'feels exactly like the real thing',
explained Cliff Quay's principal, Mr Brian Malloy. It can simulate
everything from escaping steam to a mouse chewing through cables.
The system, Nuclear Electric said, is infinitely more sophisticated than a
flight simulator. It is based on one of a few existing models of a nuclear
reactor core, designed by Combined Engineering of the US. It may also be
used to train nuclear industry staff from what was the Soviet Union and
eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
