<TEXT>
Bombs in Madrid yesterday damaged the Labour Ministry and the headquarters
of INI, the state-owned conglomerate that owns most of Spain's public
companies, Tom Burns reports from Madrid.
While the bombs were small and the damage slight, the explosions were a
dramatic prelude to today's May Day rallies, which will underline a growing
union revolt against government policies. In the wake of government cuts in
unemployment benefits and of plans to legislate curbs on wildcat strikes,
unions have planned a half-day general strike on May 28 and further
stoppages in October.
