<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Papers battle for black readers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE circulation battle among newspapers aimed at Britain's black population
will be heightened with today's launch of The Weekly Journal, the first
broadsheet newspaper targeted at the growing young black middle class, with
a potential readership of 1.1m.
Black readers are already served by at least four other papers. The
10-year-old tabloid weekly The Voice has a circulation of 47,000, double
that of the Caribbean Times, its nearest rival.
Black Briton claims weekly sales of 20,000. The Weekly Gleaner, owned by
Gleaner Group of Jamaica, and first published in the UK in 1951, has a
circulation of 15,000.
Most of these papers rely on the public sector for the bulk of their
advertising.
The Weekly Journal is owned by Voice Communications, publishers of The
Voice, which is being challenged by Black Briton, a middle-market tabloid
launched last August by a former assistant editor of The Voice.
The Voice reacted to the launch of Black Briton with a hastily arranged
reorganisation, new features and an advertising campaign.
Reporters say they were threatened with legal action if they left The Voice
and joined Black Briton within a year. Former staff members who had agreed
to join Black Briton - and in some cases had started work on it - were lured
back with greatly enhanced financial packages.
Critics say The Weekly Journal was devised as a spoiler. With a print run of
40,000, it is aimed at young, educated, upwardly mobile blacks in the ABC1
socio-economic groups.
Under its main title, a strapline says 'For today's Black Briton'.
Mr Diran Adebayo, a former journalist on The Voice who left the paper last
year and now works for the BBC, said the new title 'was conceived as a
spoiler. The only strong reason for its launch is to counter Black Briton.'
Mr Val McCalla, chairman of Voice Communications, said: 'The launch of Black
Briton did act as a catalyst for the launch of the new paper. It became
clear after Black Briton's launch that it was not satisfying the market.
'There is a gap in the market for a more authoritative, reliable and
informative broadsheet from a black viewpoint such as The Journal. Black
Briton is not right for that market. It is just trying to replicate The
Voice.'
Mr Joseph Harker, publisher and editor of Black Briton, said of Mr McCalla's
new venture: 'I think he's on a loser and I'd advise him to put his money
elsewhere.'
The new paper is launched against a background of the continuing recession
in advertising. Nevertheless, Mr McCalla says he is prepared to support The
Weekly Journal for 'as long as it takes to make it a success'.
Mr Werbayne McIntyre, a partner at WM&amp;P, a black advertising and marketing
consultancy, said: 'Judging by the advertising in Black Briton, if it
doesn't increase its advertising revenue, it is difficult to see how it will
sustain itself.'
Mr McIntyre believes that there is a place for a paper such as The Weekly
Journal and says that it should survive, especially if it can attract
display advertising from the private sector.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-10471</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CD3BPAGSFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920430
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / London Stock Exchange: Utilities race ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO, COLIN MILLHAM and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LOOMING results season for the utilities and the above-average yield
attractions of the water, electricity and power generation stocks triggered
a flurry of demand for all three sectors.
County NatWest was said to have been among the keenest supporters of the
spread of utilities. Ms Rachel Lucas, at County, said the sectors offered
considerable potential following the general election result. County
especially favours the regional electricity companies and the generators
which, according to the broker, stand to gain most from growing perceptions
in the market that the recent national grid report on overcapacity is
implausible.
County was particularly keen on utilities reporting early in the season,
including North West Water, up 9 at 422p; South West Water, 6 higher at
421p; and Norweb Electricity, 8 ahead at 343p. National Power rose 6 to
227p.
Glaxo gain limited
Pharmaceutical group Glaxo Holdings retreated following the dramatic fall
and suspension of shares in Toronto of an allied company.
Glaxo had started brightly in London, along with the other leading drugs
stocks, putting on 18 by midday. However, as Toronto opened, Biochem Pharma,
which is developing its 3TC anti-Aids drug exclusively for Glaxo, requested
a suspension after seeing its shares plunge, and talk in the London market
erroneously put this down to problems with the new drug.
The group's request came as a result of rumours that it had run into
difficulties with a share placement, due to be made by US broking house
Morgan Stanley. Biochem shares resumed trading after London had closed and
ended sharply down. The company said it was not aware of any reason for the
decline, and said it intends to proceed with an issue of up to 3.5m common
shares in late May. Glaxo closed in London 2 up at 738p.
Banks weaker
Trade in Midland Bank slowed to only 8.1m shares, compared with 27m on
Tuesday, as the market continued to take on board implications of the bid
situation. The stock slipped 7 1/2 to 386 1/2 p after the bank again
recommended the offer from Hongkong and Shanghai Banking. Rival bidder
Lloyds Bank lost 2 to 415p.
Analysts suggested that there may be sizeable arbitrage trade between shares
in Lloyds and Midland over the next few months, with prices reflecting
whether investors believe the Lloyds bid will succeed. At present the
cheapest way into a combined Lloyds/Midland group is through Midland.
Barclays declined 6 to 347p on continuing worries about its exposure to the
debt of property company Olympia &amp; York.
Institutional buyers snapped up Williams Holdings' 9.8 per cent stake in
Racal, the 130m shares being placed by SG Warburg at 58 1/2 p. Williams,
which collected Pounds 81m from the sale, closed 7 firmer at 352p. Racal
held at 60 1/2 p.
RTZ jumped 23 to 635p in brisk turnover of 2.9m. There was talk that a
strike in Chile, the world's largest copper producer, could benefit RTZ, and
also that the company had sold part of its industrial division.
Speculation of a takeover offer from Minorco lifted Lonrho 7 to 98p.
British Airways was in demand ahead of the annual meeting later this month.
The shares gained 9 to 280p as a hefty 9.2m were traded.
Vodafone slipped 6 to 351p in busy volume of 5.6m as James Capel downgraded
the telecoms group.
Fisons, up 18 at 384p, led a strong drugs sector, with the market keen to
anticipate a positive decision by the US Food and Drugs Adminstration, which
is examining Fisons' Holmes Chapel facility.
Presentations by Wellcome over the next few days, and in the US next week,
ahead of its share issue helped the stock rise 7 to 1036p.
Whitbread 'A' climbed 13 to 457p, outperforming the rest of the sector on
hopes of recovery. Mr Mike McCarthy, breweries analyst at Smith New Court,
said Whitbread has the most recovery potential among national brewers.
UBS Phillips &amp; Drew took Travis Perkins, which reported results in line with
expectations yesterday, off its buy list following the builders merchant's
recent good run. The shares were unchanged at 224p. The broker is
recommending a switch into Wolseley, off 8 at 453p, or Meyer International,
down 3 at 415p.
Two crosses by a leading agency broker in Costain Group - one of 1.4m shares
at 81 1/2 p and another of 2.5m at 82p - lifted the day's turnover for the
stock to 8.5m. The shares put on 2 to 81p.
Selected construction issues advanced on offical figures showing a rise in
orders for the first quarter.
The long-awaited finance deal between Greycoat and a consortium of banks for
the property group's Embankment Place development in central London lifted
it 7 to 61p.
Talk that ICI's first-quarter results today will contain some good news
pushed the shares 11 higher to 1381p. A shortage of stock in BOC Group
squeezed it up 13 to 726p.
Among supermarkets, Tesco receded 9 to 282p on turnover of 5.4m shares
following a recommendation by BZW to switch into J. Sainsbury. The latter
was unchanged at 433p as the sector continued to react nervously to Credit
Lyonnais Laing's criticism of property valuation and accounting policies.
Dixons was off just a penny at 256p in hefty turnover of 3.1m shares after
recovering most of an early loss caused by a profits downgrade from County
NatWest.
