</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RIO ALGOM, Canadian subsidiary of the UK mining group RTZ, suffered a
two-thirds drop in first-quarter earnings on lower mineral prices and stiff
competition in the metals distribution business, writes Bernard Simon.
But Mr Colin Macaulay, chief executive, told yesterday's annual meeting that
the company was continuing to seek sizeable base-metal acquisitions, mainly
in North America. Rio Algom has earmarked a large chunk of its cash
reserves, which totalled CDollars 180m (USDollars 151m) on December 31, for
takeovers.
Net earnings skidded to CDollars 4.9m from CDollars 14m a year earlier.
Mr Macaulay said 1992 earnings would be similar to the 51 cents a share
earned in 1991.
