<TEXT>
FIRST National Bank (FNB), South Africa's third-largest bank, lifted net
income by 20.5 per cent to R187.8m (Dollars 65.2m) in the six months to
end-March on the back of asset growth of 18 per cent, writes Philip Gawith
in Johannesburg.
The bank recorded a 26.9 per cent increase in net interest income, to
R920.6m, and a 21.8 per cent rise in the bad debt charge, to R160.5m. Mr
Barry Swart, managing director, said the interest performance was due to the
bank's focus on profitable business. The 27 per cent rise in net interest
income came from a 20.6 per cent rise in advances. Other operating income
was 21 per cent higher at R645.4m, but was overshadowed by a 23.1 per cent
rise in other operating expenses.
