<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / International Company News: Ford returns to the black with
earnings of Dollars 338m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FORD Motor yesterday under-scored the gradual recovery under way in the US
car market with its first profit since the third quarter of 1990.
General Motors, the biggest US vehicle manufacturer, on Tuesday reported its
first profit after six quarters of red ink.
Both companies were hit hard last year by a slump in demand during the US
recession, which led to heavy price discounting. They are now being helped
by a modest pick-up in orders, resulting in lower rebates and sweeping
cost-cutting programmes.
Ford surprised analysts by also reporting a net profit of Dollars 84m from
its European operations, compared with a loss of Dollars 129m in the same
period of last year.
Most surprising of all, the company made a small profit in the UK after
record 1991 losses.
The company said group earnings for the quarter totalled Dollars 338m, or 60
cents a share, on sales of Dollars 24.6bn, compared with a net loss of
Dollars 884m, or Dollars 1.88, on sales of Dollars 21.34bn a year ago.
Mr Harold Poling, chairman, warned that a continuation of the turnround
would depend greatly on a sustained recovery in the US and other key
markets. 'Although industry sales in the US remained weak in the first
quarter, there are signs of an improving trend,' Mr Poling added.
Ford's US automotive operations earned Dollars 57m, against a loss of
Dollars 947m a year ago. However, the business was only put into the black
by a Dollars 61m gain from the sale of a computer concern.
Overseas, the group earned Dollars 28m, compared with a loss of Dollars
208m.
The financial services group contributed Dollars 253m, down Dollars 18m,
which the company attributed to one-off gains a year ago.
Ford officials said reasons for the US improvement included a sharp
reduction in heavily discounted sales to wholesale fleet buyers, which
dropped from 37 per cent of vehicle sales to 29 per cent.
Despite this, the company's share of the US car market rose one percentage
point from the full-year 1991 level, to 21.1 per cent.
Despite the improvement in Britain, Ford's Jaguar luxury car business lost
'a little' less than Dollars 100m, according to a company official, against
a loss of 'a little more' than Dollars 100m a year ago.
