<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Call for fuller company reports: Accountancy body seeks
disclosure of more details by all quoted groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES should help share-holders by providing far more detailed comments
on their activities in annual reports, says the UK accountancy standards
body.
A new 'operating and financial review' statement should give a balanced,
objective statement of good and bad news, the Accounting Standards Board
recommends in draft proposals issued yesterday. It should include operating
results, financial needs and resources and shareholder value, and should be
written in an accessible style.
Mr David Tweedie, the board's chairman, said: 'What we're after is
management going behind the numbers and helping people understand their
business. I suspect many private shareholders will read this rather than the
accounts.' The suggestions are likely to lead to a statement of best
practice rather than the legally enforceable accounting standards the board
has been producing until now.
It would not be audited because it is not part of the accounts. But one
option being considered is whether auditors should be required to approve
the statement to ensure it complies with the guidelines.
Discussion of the ideas will lead to an exposure draft in the late autumn
and could be converted into a formal statement early next year.
The board would like this to apply to all the quoted companies, as well as
other businesses, including the private companies and large entities in the
public sector.
Among the more important items which the discussion paper says companies
should discuss are:
the main risks and uncertainties facing the company, including environmental
protection costs and liabilities; dependence on important customers or
sources of scarce raw materials; and the impact of exchange rate changes on
the results;
the current capital structure of the enterprise including the purpose and
impact of financial transactions undertaken; acquisitions and disposals; and
current solvency and liquidity, with details of peak borrowing requirements
and facilities;
the strengths and resources of the business with value which is not
adequately reflected in the balance sheet, such as brand names and other
intangible items.
The statement will not require profit forecasts and future projections, but
should look forward as well as backward and help users in making their own
projections of future results.
The review should be the responsibility of all the directors, and might
ultimately replace either the existing directors' report or the chief
executive's review included in existing annual reports.
* Operating and financial review discussion paper. Free. Accounting
Standards Board, 100 Gray's Inn Rd, London WC1X 8AL.
R&amp;D plea, Page 8
How to improve the profession's image, Page 12
Policing problems, Page 25
</TEXT>
