<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Bitter-sweet win awaits Labour: The battle for control of a
city council
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ENTERPRISE and local government are hardly bedfellows, but things are
changing. Gloucester City Council has moved, mayor and all, from the ancient
Guildhall to an industrial warehouse on the edge of its now-defunct docks.
The council paid Pounds 1 for its new home; it let the Guildhall for Pounds
3m - and in the process helped make the dockland a business and tourist
magnet.
Gloucester's docks symbolise Labour's trauma in middle England. They closed
a few years after the defeat of the city's last Labour MP in 1970, and the
city has had a Tory MP ever since.
Yet Labour is the largest party on the city council - on which no party has
overall control - and in next week's local elections looks set to make the
single gain needed to take overall control. For Mr Kevin Stephens, leader of
the Labour group on the council, it will be a bitter-sweet triumph: as the
party's general election candidate, he was more than 6,000 votes behind the
Tory.
Why do the Tories enjoy national success but local failure? 'It's national
factors: poll tax, cuts and the like,' says Mr Michael Pullon, Gloucester's
Tory leader. 'Every year's local elections offer a chance to protest.' The
Tory collapse has been steep and rapid: they ran the council until 1989, and
in 10 years have dropped from 23 to 10 councillors (out of a total of 33).
The election is taking a now-typical course: Labour almost unchallenged on
the council estates of Matson, Tuffley and Coney Hill; the Tories competing
with them in more 'mixed' areas; and a separate Tory-Liberal Democrat
contest in the leafy groves of Kingsholme and Hucclecote. The Liberal
Democrats' seven seats were all gained from the Tories. 'It's a secure but
narrow base', says Mrs Mary Gould, the Liberal Democrat group's leader.
The political battle on the council has an unreal quality. There are
divisions aplenty, and real bitterness two years ago over plans by the
outgoing Tory administration to hand the council's entire housing stock  -
6,200 tenants - to a housing association.
Yet reacting to government policy - and working within its constraints  - is
the main preoccupation of all three parties. All supported a poll tax
(Pounds 309) at the government capping level - arguing mainly about how much
should go to voluntary organisations.
All are relieved that the city's manual-labour contracts were won by its own
workforce.
Furthermore, all are ardent supporters of the 'historic cities group',
campaigning for the restoration of unitary county boroughs in cathedral
cities. 'We have little in common with the rural parts of the county - 10
per cent of our population are from ethnic minorities, for a start,' says Mr
Stephens. Were the group to succeed and education pass from the county to
the city council, battles over Gloucester's four grammar schools might
ensue. But with two opted-out and the others likely to follow, even there
scope for intervention is contracting.
Housing policy highlights the tensions graphically. For all the opprobium he
attracted for his housing association plan, Mr Pullon is critical of
government-imposed restraints, particularly the refusal to allow local
authorities to use capital receipts for social housing.
On having sunk Mr Pullon's housing association venture, Labour and the
Liberal Democrats are now launching one of their own. The city council is
proposing to grant land and development rights to Oxbode, a new association
of whose 15 directors three will be from the council. If it secures
registration, the association will use council land and funds from the
Housing Corporation and private lenders to build social housing.
Mrs Gould is candid: 'Oxbode was really seen an escape route for us if the
Tories won - and we need it now if there is to be any new low-rent housing
at all.'
It is a similar picture with council services. 'Quality, accountability and
efficiency are our watchwords', says Mr Stephens. If Labour takes over, he
plans customer contracts, an autonomous ombudsman to deal with complaints,
and proper redress for failures. On compulsory tendering, his fear is that
white-collar employees are not showing 'as great a realisation as the
blue-collar unions of the impact - and the need to respond'.
The three leaders unite on another theme: the growing difficulty in finding
people willing to stand for election, and the need for salaried councillors.
'We've got a Pounds 34m annual turnover: you've got to pay the going rate to
get good managers,' says Mr Pullon.
CONSERVATIVE councils will force pupils to 'pay as they learn', the Labour
party said yesterday.
Mr Jack Straw, the shadow education secretary, campaigning for next week's
local government elections, said free state education was under threat and
parents would have to pay more and more for their children's schooling
because of government spending limits.
The elections would be about 'higher standards in schools, better value for
money and a rejection of the Tories' policy of 'pay as you learn',' he said.
He said one Kent school, which he refused to name, was already charging
pupils Pounds 12 each to buy essential books. A report last year found
parents were paying Pounds 50m a year for classroom essentials.
Mr Straw said other Conservative local education authorities were being
forced to cut budgets to meet government spending targets. Many were leaving
teacher vacancies unfilled and were planning new staff cuts.
</TEXT>
