<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Social Europe: Brussels may force clock watchers into a
re-think - The implications for British companies and their workers of the
EC directive on working time
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 2m British workers who work more than 48 hours each week, and the
thousands of companies they work for, may have to re-think radically if
European Community employment ministers today reach outline agreement on the
EC working time directive.
If agreement is not reached today it will come at the ministers' meeting in
June and, although the government is likely to oppose it, the directive may
become part of UK law within months.
The 'opt-out' from the next stage of EC employment legislation won by the
government at the Maastricht summit was too late to fend off the directive.
Because it has been introduced under health and safety legislation, it
requires only a qualified majority - at least one other big EC country plus
a small one, or three smaller countries, must side with the UK to block it.
British officials believe there is a new willingness to do a deal with the
UK, especially with Mrs Gillian Shephard, the new employment secretary in
the chair, and that a high degree of flexibility in implementing the
directive might be allowed at national level.
The UK's preferred option is to allow work over 48 hours provided people
have passed a health risk assessment.
If the UK government is not satisfied with the outcome, it will probably
launch a legal challenge to the health and safety basis of the directive.
Alternatively, it may simply refuse to implement the directive and wait for
the EC Commission to take it to the European Court of Justice.
Either way, there is no certainty that the UK would win.
The directive includes:
A ceiling on the working week of 48 hours including overtime, averaged
within a reference period, likely to be set at four months.
A minimum daily rest period of 11 hours, with Sunday 'in principle' treated
as a day of rest. That principle can be broken with impunity but is still
unpopular with the UK government because of the support it gives to the
anti-Sunday trading lobby.
Minimum annual paid holiday of four weeks - three weeks for the first three
years of the directive.
Some groups of workers, including managers, the self-employed and transport
workers, are exempt from the directive and there are 'derogations' for other
groups that allow particular measures such as the 48-hour week to be
breached but insist on 'compensatory rest'.
The proposals - particularly the 48-hour limit - would seem a classic case
of the EC's legislative norms being imposed upon the UK's more flexible
system of industrial relations.
Almost all other EC countries, apart from the Irish Republic and Denmark,
have had detailed legislation in those areas for decades.
Partly as a result, there is a much stronger convergence of working time in
other EC countries and far fewer people working more than 48 hours.
The EC's average working week is close to 40 hours, but 36 per cent of
workers in the UK work between 35 and 40 hours a week, compared with 72 per
cent in the rest of the community.
The UK has a much higher incidence of part-time work and of long hours - for
full-time workers, the UK has the longest average working week in the EC at
45.5 hours. British workers also do more overtime and more shift-work than
those elsewhere in the EC.
A total of 2.7m British employees - 11.7 per cent of the workforce -
regularly work more than 48 hours per week, far more than elsewhere else in
the EC.
There is a high concentration among particular groups of workers - rail
workers, farm workers, crane drivers, food industry workers - mainly as a
result of high overtime. But Department of Employment economists say there
is a sprinkling of over-48-hour working in almost all industries.
The cost to British industry of maintaining output while complying with the
directive is impossible to calculate. The government's estimate of Pounds
5bn - of which Pounds 3.5bn comes from the 48-hour limit - is very rough.
Some managers say it is good management to cut chronic overtime. Some
companies, such as ICI, are not enthusiastic, but say they live with such
restrictions on the Continent. With a little reorganisation they could do so
here.
Nevertheless, the bulk of UK companies strongly oppose the directive and
fear higher costs unless productivity can be correspondingly raised.
Much will depend on how quickly it has to be introduced and how adaptable
employees can be.
</TEXT>
