FT  30 APR 92 / Minister gives reasons for City regulation move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ANTHONY NELSON, economic secretary to the Treasury, has explained
publicly for the first time the government's reasons for a planned upheaval
in the regulation of financial markets.
He also restated the government's intention to oppose proposed EC
legislation that might threaten the UK's securities industry.
Mr Nelson said responsibility for regulation of financial markets and
non-bank financial services would not be shifted from the Department of
Trade and Industry to the Treasury for a 'month or so'.
It is understood that legal difficulties have delayed the move, which was
announced in the Conservative manifesto.
Mr Nelson said the switch reflected developments in financial markets. 'The
barriers between the different industries are crumbling,' he said, and it
made sense to bring together regulation of both the bank and non-bank
sector. It would give more weight to the UK financial sector's views
internationally.
Mr Nelson said: 'If UK interests are to be represented and expressed as
effectively as possible, they should be concentrated in one department and
one set of ministers.' The dividing line on big fraud cases between City
regulators and criminal investigators should be reconsidered, Mr Christopher
Sharples, chairman of the Securities and Futures Authority, said. 'There may
well be advantages in allowing City regulation, with its ability to act
quickly and get results on a much less legalistic basis, to deal with some
of the alleged offences at the outset.' He added that that might apply
particularly 'when they are of a nature more akin to breaches of City codes
or ethics or market misconduct, rather than fraud or theft in the
traditional sense.'
