FT  30 APR 92 / Business leaders call for support from Heseltine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDUSTRIALISTS yesterday called on Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry
secretary, to end years of alleged ministerial misunderstanding about the
needs of British manufacturing industry and to champion its cause at home
and abroad. Mr Heseltine was given the message at a meeting with members of
the Confederation of British Industry's National Manufacturing Council, set
up to promote the manufacturing sector. The session with 50 leading
industrialists was his first outside engagement since taking over the
department.
He was told industry wanted, above all, a champion for business in
Whitehall, at Westminster and in Brussels.
Those responsible for UK and EC legislation had to be asked to examine its
effect on business, in particular in respect of costs.
With Mr Heseltine long-pledged to make his department a more powerful
advocate of industry's interests throughout government, he will have readily
welcomed the CBI's views, although the meeting was primarily billed as an
opportunity for him to listen rather than to respond. Since his appointment,
Mr Heseltine has not given any public indication of his detailed ambitions
for the DTI, but he is due to make his first keynote speech next week.
The DTI last night had no comment to make on the talks, which it said formed
part of Mr Heseltine's initial dialogue with the business community.
The CBI, which was critical of the government's relations with industry
under several of Mr Heseltine's predecessors, said it wanted him to stand up
for industry inside the Civil Service and government, within the European
community and other export markets. The CBI said after the meeting: 'In the
past, UK industry has been ill-understood by the DTI and its interests have
been subordinated to the interests of more powerful departments like the
Treasury. Business needs to be properly represented in the corridors of
power.'
The CBI said it was very important that the DTI understood the importance of
wealth creation and the international competitive pressures on different
industrial sectors.
It was made clear that industry was not looking to the DTI for subsidies or
handouts but it was concerned to ensure that it was not placed at a
disadvantage by financial and other forms of assistance given to competitors
by other governments.
The CBI also called on Mr Heseltine to help improve export promotion and to
encourage the development of Training and Enterprise Councils.
