<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Institutions tackle 'short-termism'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INSTITUTIONAL shareholders are asking companies to tell them more about
their investments in research and development in an effort to counteract
charges that shareholders are short-term in their outlook.
Companies have complained that they are discouraged from spending on R&amp;D by
shareholders who would rather see money spent on bigger dividends or on
acquisitions.
The Bank of England-backed Institutional Shareholders Committee will today
announce a suggested format for companies beyond principles established by
the Accountancy Standards Board.
'This paper attempts to break the impasse by setting out those facts about
R&amp;D that it would be useful for institutional investors to know. The onus is
now with companies to provide that information,' the ISC said.
Mr Michael Sandland, chief investment officer at Norwich Union and ISC
chairman, said he believed companies would adopt the new format, even though
it was voluntary. 'If this document came out two years ago, it would have
been laughed at,' he said. 'But now I think it will lead the way.'
The drive for improved corporate governance and the concurrent demands of
shareholders for more information were likely to encourage companies to
comply, he said.
The proposals urge each industry to establish its own detailed definition of
R&amp;D to invite comparisons of expenditure among similar companies. It urges a
particularly broad interpretation of development costs and asks companies to
disclose all those relating to existing products and services as well as
those under development.
Companies are also urged to spell out which of their research expenditure is
'pure' or applied to specific products, along with a discussion of the
potential returns from each category of expenditure.
Because the information is broader than that required by the ASB, the
shareholders' group suggests that companies disclose it in annual reports or
in separate presentations to shareholders rather than in corporate accounts.
The ISC proposed the rules after it was approached by the Electrical
Equipment Association, an electronics trade body, whose members were
concerned about short-termism.
</TEXT>
