that Lloyd's might be jeopardising its long-term future by short-term and
unco-ordinated responses to its present difficulties.
Ms Julianne Jessup, director of De Lisle Jessup Scott, mergers and
acquisitions specialists for the insurance sector, said at a conference that
Lloyd's agents were shifting the focus of their business away from high-risk
areas because that was superficially more attractive to Names.
Ms Jessup also said it was difficult to see how corporate capital - which
the Rowland task force recommended should be introduced to the market -
could co-exist with Names' underwriting on an unlimited basis.
Reliance on corporate capital would almost inevitably change the structure
of Lloyd's and erode its ability to be innovative and flexible.
