<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Fresh clashes erupt in Sarajevo: European Community
struggles to get peace talks started in Lisbon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and PATRICK BLUM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, LISON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FIGHTING last night broke out in nearly every quarter of Sarajevo, capital
of Bosnia-Hercegovina, between the republic's mainly Moslem defence forces
and Serb irregulars.
The clashes - the most serious in the city since last Thursday - were
reported by Sarajevo television and came just hours after Serbian TV
announced that Moslem forces in Bosnia had effectively declared war against
the Serbian-dominated federal army.
Bosnian officials claimed no such order had been given and accused the Serbs
of a trick to make it look as if they wanted war. Fighting also erupted last
night in the republic's southern city of Mostar.
The reports on Serbia's Belgrade TV were based on a despatch by Tanjug, the
Belgrade-based news agency which reflects Serbian views. This said the
Territorial Defence organisation had called for 'the stepping-up of all
battle activities' on Bosnian territory and a mass blockade of all federal
army installations in Bosnia.
Tanjug appears to have based its own despatch on a statement made earlier
yesterday by Colonel Vehbija Karic, a leader of the Bosnian forces, in which
he called on the republic's inhabitants and all Territorial Defence units to
stop unauthorised removal of army equipment and the movement of army troops
not escorted by the Territorial Defence.
European Community observers stationed in three towns in Bosnia were
recalled to their headquarters for consultations yesterday but also because
their security could no longer be guaranteed.
In Lisbon, meanwhile, leaders of the republic's three national communities
gathered for EC-sponsored peace talks. Leaders of Bosnia's Slavic Moslems,
Serbs and Croats appear to agree only that the urgent despatch of United
Nations troops could curb the violence; beyond that, the warring factions
remain far apart.
Preliminary bilateral talks continued into the evening, with the opening of
full discussions being continually delayed. Officials hoped the arrival of
Mr Aliza Izetbegovic, Bosnia's Moslem president, would be the beginning of
substantive talks, but prospects were dimmed when he said he could only be
there for a day. 'I have come here to explain the situation . . . to the
European Community,' he said.
Funding the UN peace-keeping force in Croatia created serious problems for
the secretariat in New York and the international community has indicated
its considerable reluctance to become involved still further.
Meanwhile, the EC and the US appear to have backed down from warnings to
Serbia of political and economic isolation for its role in destabilising
Bosnia. Instead, they appear to have given President Slobodan Milosevic
leeway to try to stop the fighting by bringing paramilitary units to heel.
Diplomatic pressure on Mr Milosevic eased somewhat when the US revised its
position and placed part of the blame for the violence on Croatia, which it
suspects of aiming to divide Bosnia with Serbia.
Economic sanctions, it is argued in Belgrade, risk strengthening support for
Mr Milosevic by bolstering popular resentment of 'western interference'.
Many fear further detoriation of the economy would give rise to an ultra
nationalist administration. Sanctions would also hurt the already hard-hit
economies of Bosnia and the independence-seeking Macedonia.
Hunger already threatens Bosnia's 4.35m inhabitants. Serb road blocks have
all but stopped the transport of foodstuffs and relief supplies. Serbia has
banned most exports of food to Bosnia. Factories, not yet damaged by war,
have had to cut production for lack of raw materials.
A PORTUGUESE spokesman said yesterday that European Community recognition of
the new Yugoslav republic would depend on its fulfilling three basic
conditions, writes Patrick Blum in Lisbon. It would have to withdraw its
troops from all neighbouring states, accept the terms of the peace
conference aiming to reach a peaceful solution to the conflict, and show
willing to negotiate with all the other states of the former Yugoslav
republic on the division of its assets and liabilities.
</TEXT>
