<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / AT&amp;T offers a telephone number for life
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AMERICANS are to be offered a personal telephone number for life, the
perfect accessory for a nation whose citizens move house an average of 11
times.
In June, AT&amp;T, the US telecommunications group, will introduce a personal
telephone number that will allow subscribers to be reached at any telephone
in the continental US.
AT&amp;T's Easy Reach 700 service provides subscribers with a personal
identification number - their own access number to the service. The number
need not change if the subscriber moves house within the US.
Although call-forwarding is already available, Easy Reach subscribers not
only have a number for life but can also select which calls they want
forwarded to them at any location.
At Dollars 7 (Pounds 3.90) a month the service will not be cheap for
consumers used to receiving telephone numbers free. Calls within the US will
cost 25 cents a minute between 8am and 5pm and 15 cents a minute at other
times.
The idea of personal telephone numbers has been mooted in Europe, but most
European countries see it as 10 years away.
BT price cut urged, Page 10
