<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Attack on Kohl intensifies feud within coalition: Germany's
future deputy chancellor calls for stronger leadership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Helmut Kohl, faced with spreading strikes across Germany,
yesterday came under attack from his future deputy chancellor who called for
stronger leadership and drastic budget cuts.
The call, from Mr Jurgen Mollemann, the economics minister who has just been
nominated for the deputy's post, fuelled the bitter feuding between the
parties that make up Germany's ruling coalition.
The recriminations followed Monday's dramatic decision by Mr Hans-Dietrich
Genscher to resign as foreign minister and deputy chancellor - and
disagreements within the government over who should succeed him.
At the same time, the Bavarian Christian Social Union (CSU), sister party of
Mr Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU), bitterly criticised Mr Mollemann
and his Free Democratic party (FDP) for upsetting the coalition, and called
on Mr Kohl to carry out a drastic government reshuffle.
For their part the opposition Social Democrats (SPD), taking advantage of
the obvious confusion in government ranks, called for new elections two
years ahead of time.
The FDP yesterday attempted to close ranks after a revolt by its members of
parliament, who rejected the leadership's nomination of Mrs Irmgard
Schwaetzer as new foreign minister, and substituted Mr Klaus Kinkel, the
present justice minister.
At the same time, the party is insisting on Mr Mollemann as its candidate
for deputy chancellor, although he is unpopular with the coalition partners.
That is the job which the CSU believes should now go to Mr Theo Waigel, its
leader and the current finance minister.
Mr Mollemann has chosen just this moment to launch an offensive on the
government's spending plans, delivering a 16-page paper to Mr Waigel calling
for drastic budget cuts, according to today's issue of the independent
Suddeutsche Zeitung.
Mr Mollemann also called for urgent action to privatise significant state
holdings such as Lufthansa, the German airline, Deutsche Telekom, the state
telecommunications monopoly, and the post office savings bank, in order to
raise more cash.
The report says he is calling for a common line from the chancellor, the
finance minister and his own economics ministry, proposing cuts - including
a reduction in social spending, an area which Mr Kohl has specifically ruled
out for savings. Mr Mollemann also called for 'strong political leadership'
in Bonn, the newspaper said, clearly implying weakness in the chancellor.
The timing of his initiative has fuelled speculation that the FDP may be
seeking a confrontation with its coalition partners, given the sliding
popularity of the government in the opinion polls, and the ever-more
unpopular costs of paying for unification with eastern Germany.
In his paper, Mr Mollemann argues that the budget faces increased charges
totalling billions of D-Marks from compensation costs related to unification
 -DM10bn (Pounds 3.4bn) in 1993, DM15bn in 1994 and DM25bn in 1995.
Mr Kohl is simultaneously facing grumblings of discontent from the CSU,
whose leader, Mr Waigel, does not appear to have been seriously consulted
over the Genscher succession.
Last night the party and parliamentary leaders of the three coalition
partners were meeting in an attempt to agree on their outstanding
differences, including the question of budget strategy in the coming months.
Mr Peter Struck, the SPD parliamentary group manager, said there was a
simple answer to the coalition's crisis: new elections.
