<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Labour may end role of unions in leadership elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ROLE of trade unions in the election of Labour leaders could end this
autumn, it emerged yesterday, as the party ordered an inquest into what went
wrong in its general election campaign.
Labour's packaging of policy was also under attack last night from deputy
leader Mr Roy Hattersley, who told ITN that the Sheffield election rally
'epitomised five to 10 years of mistakes'.
The move to end the unions' role would significantly reduce the party's
historic links with the trade unions. It follows mounting criticism of their
conduct in the current leadership contest, not least the refusal of several
of the largest to ballot members.
Front runner in the leadership race, Mr John Smith, meanwhile, was putting
the finishing touches to a 6,000-word manifesto to be launched today aimed
at quashing criticism that he has so far offered few new ideas.
A novel proposal in the document is for a 'special commission' into social
justice aimed at creating a broad non-Tory consensus on how to reconcile
pressing social needs without unduly raising the tax burden.
It would ally political parties with interest groups and aim to put fresh
pressure on the government.
The shadow chancellor will also emphasise his intention to run an open-door
leadership, responsive to the views of all sections of the party.
Mr Robin Cook, his campaign manager, said last night: 'He wants the
leadership election to open up debate about the future, not to close it
down.'
Labour's national executive committee had agreed that the rules for future
leadership elections should be reviewed immediately and the review completed
before the party's conference in October, Mr Larry Whitty, Labour's general
secretary, said.
He would not rule out the possibility of ending the electoral college system
which gives 40 per cent of the votes to unions and 30 per cent each for MPs
and individual members.
The current leadership battle between Mr Smith and Mr Bryan Gould, which
will be over by July 18, would not be affected by any changes.
Meanwhile, plans for an investigation into Labour's election defeat were
under way, as members of the NEC asked the organisation committee to conduct
a comprehensive inquest into what went wrong, and to report before the
autumn conference.
But a preliminary assessment by Mr Whitty concluded that voters' last-minute
fears of the uncertainties over the recession and the impact of a Labour
victory had scared them into the Conservative camp. Mr Neil Kinnock, party
leader, said: 'It was a choice between fear and hope and fear was what won
out.'
Mr Hattersley said the party had to answer the question of why people's fear
of Labour had cost it the election. There were two or three explanations.
'Certainly the lies about Labour tax policy frightened a lot of people. The
question is why we didn't overcome those lies,' he said.
Criticising the emphasis on packaging, he told ITN: 'We have packaged our
product wonderfully. We have packaged it so well that too many people have
described the package without describing the contents.'
Labour's lucky 13, Page 8
Editorial comment, Page 20
</TEXT>
