<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Midland softens support for Hongkong takeover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MIDLAND BANK softened its support for Hongkong and Shanghai Bank's Pounds
3.3bn takeover bid yesterday in the wake of Lloyds' Pounds 3.6bn offer
proposal.
As the battle for control of Midland gained momentum, it also emerged that
National Australia Bank (NAB), which owns the Yorkshire and Clydesdale
banks, has told Lloyds it would be interested in buying several hundred of
Lloyds' and Midland's branches if Lloyds succeeded in buying Midland.
Lloyds was encouraged by the first official announcement from Midland since
it made its offer proposal. Midland's board said it 'intends . . . to
recommend Hongkong Bank's offer, provided this would not conflict with the
ability of Midland shareholders to consider a firm offer from Lloyds which
secured demonstrably greater value for their shares'.
Under the terms of the takeover code, this does not constitute a firm
recommendation in favour of Hongkong Bank's bid. A Midland director said:
'The recommendation is slightly on the shelf.'
The Midland statement was approved by the board after a two-hour meeting
with the bank's advisers on Tuesday evening. Directors felt they could not
dismiss Lloyds' offer because it was proposing to offer more than Hongkong
Bank.
Mr Brian Pearse, Midland's chief executive, said the board had to take into
account the interests of the bank's shareholders. But he pointed out that
Lloyds had not made a formal bid and would do so only if it was not
obstructed by the EC and UK competition authorities.
Meanwhile, it also emerged that NAB's merchant bank adviser, Lazard
Brothers, has told Lloyds' chief executive, Mr Brian Pitman, that NAB would
be interested in buying Midland and Lloyds branches. NAB has already
acquired several hundred branches from Midland, having bought Midland's
Clydesdale and northern subsidiaries in 1987.
Lloyds is considering the NAB approach, but is unlikely to begin detailed
negotiations for several weeks. It has been considering whether it would
avoid having its proposal to acquire Midland being being referred to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission, the UK competition authority, if it were
to agree to sell branches.
Lloyds believes an MMC reference is probably inevitable and is concentrating
on persuading the Department of Trade and Industry to also refer Hongkong
Bank's bid to the MMC. However, Lloyds may try to do a deal with NAB or
another bank at a later stage, during the MMC investigation, to persuade the
MMC not to block a Midland takeover.
In a separate development, it emerged that there is considerable legal
uncertainty over a key article in the EC Merger Regulation, which will
determine whether Hongkong Bank's bid falls under the jurisdiction of UK
competition authorities or the EC authority. The article refers to the
location of bank assets.
