<PROFILE>_AN-CD3BPADOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920430
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Survey of Relocation in The UK (13): British Gas plans to
relocate 1,300 London staff
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH GAS is preparing to relocate 1,300 employees from London to a new
300,000 sq. ft headquarters to be built at Birmingham Business Park.
The site was chosen after a detailed examination of potential venues
throughout the east and west Midlands.
The British Gas building, which should be ready by the end of 1994, will be
developed on a 20-acre plot within Arlington's 39-acre business park,
(pictured above and below). Companies moving to the business park in the
last year included Wang, Sema, Severn Trent Water, Bull, Apricot, Charles
Haswell, the Co-op Bank and Hutchison Telecommun- ications.
They joined other companies such as Rank Xerox, Lucas, Digital, Equitable
Life and the West Midlands Development Agency, already located there.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-10584</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CD3BPADNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920430
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Survey of Relocation in The UK (12): Moving closer to the
customers - Staff relocations are seldom easy, but in a phased move, Norwich
Union's first wave of employees to Sheffield 'has eased the fears of the
waverers'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN REGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NORWICH UNION'S decision to transfer a large slice of its life and pensions
operation from Norwich to Sheffield was based on both economic and strategic
considerations. However, as with most relocations that are taking place
during this recession, the economic considerations no longer apply with
quite the force they once did.
In the time-lag between the decision to move and the move itself, the
pressures which contributed to the decision have receded. Office rents in
Norwich have fallen substantially over the past 18 months, while in
Sheffield they have actually risen. The difficulty of recruiting skilled
staff, one of the prime factors in the relocation decision, has also been
eased - this time by rising unemployment.
Indeed, the job market has changed so much that the company's initial plan
to recruit most of its Sheffield workforce locally has now been changed.
Most of the 800 jobs involved will now go to those who relocate.
The strategic considerations, however, are unchanged. The company argues
that to service its customers, it needs to be geographically close to them
and a substantial operation in the north has long been seen as desirable.
The relocation involves the transfer of all the life and pensions
administration for the north-east and north-west regions.
The choice of Sheffield as a location was not made as the result of 'a
beauty contest.' Norwich Union had already expanded into the city in the
late 1980s, setting up an operation to service new distribution channels,
such as direct marketing and direct sales. It saw the relocation as an
opportunity to build on this presence.
Detailed planning for the move began in November 1990. It was approached as
a dual-track project management programme, with each region's move being
co-ordinated separately under a core team of senior managers. This approach
means that both regions must co-ordinate activity, if only to sort out
practical matters such as which floors of the new building are to be
occupied by which region. Overall project management is controlled from
Norwich.
The main challenge was to move staff within an 18-month timescale, whilst
keeping fully operational. The fact that there will be some members of staff
 -though fewer than originally anticipated - meant that the option of
transferring within a shorter time-frame did not exist.
The company decided on a phased relocation, using a three-month work cycle.
Sections of the operation are being moved and given time to gel, before the
work is transferred from Norwich. The first sections moved to the city last
July.
At present, the north-east region is half way through its relocation, with
the north-west region due to follow next year. Curiously, the north-east
region is moving temporarily into an existing Sheffield office building.
The eventual home of both regions will be a new 180,000 sq ft complex now
being built on the site of the former Rabone Chesterman tape measure
factory. The company will be a tenant in the scheme at a rent of around
Pounds 14 a sq ft, one of the highest rents ever achieved in Sheffield.
The operation will barely have time to settle before it is uprooted to its
permanent home, yet Martyn James, who is in charge of relocation the
north-east region, sees few difficulties.
'I think moving from Norwich to Sheffield is a great deal more complex than
moving within a city centre. Our next move will be like any other business
moving into new premises,' he says.
During the planning stage, Norwich Union examined several large relocations,
but failed to find anything upon which it could base the project management
of its own move.
'We looked at a lot of relocations, but couldn't find anything that
paralleled our own. As an organisation we are fairly used to moving people
around, so we actually have managers who know about relocation,' he says.
Martyn James acknowledges that one of the most difficult aspects of the move
was the initial task of finding people prepared to relocate voluntarily.
The original idea to take only those with core skills changed with the
recession, and more staff had to be persuaded to relocate.
The company, having told all its staff about the plan, advertised internally
for volunteers. This was followed by a presentation evening in Norwich at
which estate agents and educationalists from Sheffield gave brief
descriptions of the city's strengths. Coach trips to Sheffield were then
arranged to allow staff to discover the city for themselves.
The relocation package which the company already offers some key staff was
extended to all those willing to move north. This included a disturbance
allowance, up to three weeks hotel accommodation, all removal and legal
expenses and, for those with homes to sell, a guaranteed purchaser.
Despite these efforts, James admits a little disappointment at the take up -
'we would have liked more people to have come forward, but Norwich and
Sheffield are very very different places. There were a lot of
preconceptions.'
The phased nature of the move, he says, has helped considerably. The first
wave of relocating staff has eased the fears of the waverers - 'as we get
more people up here, a more positive message begins to get across.'
Thus far, he is delighted with the way the project is progressing and says
there have been few unforeseen problems.
'We always planned to do the move over 18 months, rather than trying to do
too much in one go. What we have tried to do is to start as small as
possible and build up from there.'
</TEXT>
