<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Survey of Relocation in The UK (11): Royal Armouries will
move to Leeds: There are strong economic arguments for moving historic
treasures from the Tower of Londo - The Royal Armouries found the Leeds case
unbeatable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Royal Armouries, the treasure trove which includes Henry VIII's
battledress and an entire suit of armour for an Indian elephant, have been
in the Tower of London for 900 years, so the relocation of part of the
collection was hardly likely to have been characterised by haste.
The story of the armouries began, along with schoolboy history, in 1066. The
search for a new home for part of the collection began 15 years ago, in
response to acute space problems, and is now moving rapidly towards the
planned opening of a new Pounds 35m museum at Clarence Dock, Leeds, in 1996.
The armouries are to follow the trend set by the Tate Gallery, the V&amp;A, the
Imperial War Museum, the Science Museum, and the National Portrait Gallery,
all of which have established provincial 'outstations.' The relocation of a
large part of the 40,000 items in the armouries is the result of complex
push-and-pull factors, the seeds of which were laid in 1489 when a German
visitor asked to be shown round the legendary armouries: the Tower's first
tourist. By the end of the 16th century, curious visitors were part of the
life of the Tower.
Guy Wilson, Master of the Royal Armouries, says that without a move, the
Tower was heading for serious problems by the mid-1990s because of
over-crowding. The armouries is the biggest single organisation housed in
the Tower. Some 73 per cent of the collection is usually in store because of
lack of space and the Crown Jewels are not reaping their full potential
because of the cramped conditions.
While the lack of space dictated 15 years ago that 'outstations' be found
for the collection, government policy, requiring museums to maximise their
earning potential, added momentum for radical change. Changing esthetic
standards meant that building within the Tower had to stop to preserve the
original fabric. Modern expectations in tourist presentation, requiring
audio-visual techniques, could not be used in the context of the ancient
buildings of the Tower.
Originally, a small outstation was set up at Fort Nelson, Portsmouth, to
house artillery but it was found that plans to found another for hunting and
sporting weapons were not viable. It became clear that a large part of the
collection needed to move to provide the critical mass for a major tourist
attraction.
Economic arguments were also powerful. The Royal Armouries could not charge
for admission inside the Tower and its commercial activities were restricted
within a Royal Palace and by competing retail outlets. A strategic study
concluded that earnings at the Tower could be boosted by Pounds 4m per annum
if the arms and armour collection was moved out. Benefits included extra
space for catering facilities and better presentation of the Crown Jewels.
MORI, the research organisation, was taken on to evaluate the market for a
major new museum which would allow 80 per cent of the collection to be shown
to the public at the two existing sites and the new location. MORI found
that the public was 10 per cent more likely to visit a museum based in the
north. It was expected that such a museum could attract 1.3m visitors a year
The Royal Armouries felt that the new museum should be part of an urban
tourist development. The government's efforts to bring about inner city
regeneration could also be harnessed by finding a site covered by a
development corporation. Finally, MORI had indicated that a site beside
water: like Liverpool's Albert Dock, was most likely to maximise visitor
numbers.
While most of the major conurbations in England tried to woo the Royal
Armouries, the clear winner appeared to be Sheffield, which had a strong
added advantage in its historical associations with cutlery and canon
production. The fact that Leeds won the race proves that swift action by a
local community can swing a major location decision.
Leeds Development Corporation spotted a newspaper article indicating that
Sheffield was going to get the Royal Armouries. Stuart Kenny, director of
development and marketing, telephoned the Tower - and the Leeds' bid was
underway.
Leeds felt it was vital to present a united front on the bid as a
significant financial input had to be secured to get the armouries to
abandon Sheffield. Under the umbrella of the existing Leeds Initiative,
which includes the LDC, City Council, Chamber of Commerce, Leeds University
and Polytechnic and government bodies, a financial package was put in place.
The LDC believes it can provide up to Pounds 5m for the relocation: either
through grant or land. The private sector may contribute Pounds 5m - not as
charity - but to secure a foothold in the Clarence Dock development. And
Leeds City Council hopes to provide between Pounds 2m-Pounds 4.5m.
Perhaps more than the proposed financial package, the united front from
local government, business, and the city, secured the trust of the Royal
Armouries. Lord Eden, chairman of the trustees, said: 'We chose Leeds
because of a combination of factors - its central position in the UK; its
excellent communications by road, rail, and air; the unrivalled attractions
of the Clarence Dock site, close to the city centre with its extensive
water-frontage; and the evident commitment and enthusiasm of the various
authorities, educational establishments and business representatives.'
The trustees of the Royal Armouries, and ultimately the government, found
the Leeds case unbeatable.
A creative team has been appointed to design the new museum, which will
include an outside area for jousting and falconry.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
