</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Survey of Relocation in The UK (8): New ways to ease stress
 -The psychological impact of relocation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Dr BRYAN TULLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TODAY it is widely recognised that moving home can lead a significant levels
of stress. But planners in the 1950s and '60s were nevertheless surprised
that so many former slum-dwellers pined for their old homes after they had
been relocated to improved housing.
'New town blues' characterised many relocated young families at that time,
although there was plenty of historical evidence of homesickness in other
situations where people were uprooted - for example, in the 17th century,
migrants and soldiers' described maladie du pays, a painful longing to
return home.
Furthermore, Austrian doctors in the First World War found that homesickness
was a significant factor in cases of desertion.
Psychologist Shirley Fisher of Strathclyde University has recently
investigated severe instances of homesickness which can prevent students
finishing their studies. Typical signs of severe homesickness are passivity,
depressed moods and difficulties in concentration.
Thoughts of home or memories of years spent elsewhere intrude persistently
into consciousness. Fisher found that the tendency to habitually use
fantasies about happy times elsewhere, in order to help overcome present
boredom or loneliness, can undermine a person's capacity to improve their
present situation.
Regional and international relocation for work reasons will often involve a
change for entire families. Researchers and experienced management
psychologists indicate that the 'family' is a significant cause of
assignments coming to an end prematurely. Conversely, a poorly-planned
relocation can be a strong contributor to family stress and sometimes even
to its break-up.
An increasing level of expertise - ranging from advice on housing and local
educational facilities to legal issues and counselling - is now available
from the larger business relocation agencies.
These facilities help many families avoid the stress in moving. For example,
when Nissan European Technology Centre planned their move from Sunderland to
Cranfield in 1991, they sought out a relocation company which would address
the stress issues.
Nissan chose Blackhorse Relocation Relocation Services, an offshoot of
Lloyds Bank's Black Horse estate agencies, because of its experience in
preparing people for such life changes.
The question of the 'trailing partner' (see page three) is receiving more
attention in relocations. In a recent study, Miriam Smith of Organisation
Resources Counsellors found that lack of foresight and agreement about what
the relocation is going to entail for the partner or spouse, can lead to
serious conflict later, when it may not be easily resolvable.
Miriam Smith found that relatively few companies were offering planning and
support in this area, although BP is an exception and an acknowledged
pioneer in this field.
A little imagination goes a long way in helping husbands and wives adjust to
a new location. For example, in Cleveland, a consortium of companies has a
joint clearing house for job vacancies and partners' career details.
International relocations involve the additional problems of cross-cultural
adjustment. Premature terminations of such postings are very costly in both
human and financial terms. Most people experience an initial 'honeymoon'
period of great interest and excitement, but as time passes, the 'loss' of
old friends and activities, together with new local frustrations, create
feelings of disappointment and doubt as to whether 'the big move' was really
worthwhile.
Personal suitability for making a success of international relocations
requires maturity, social skills and appropriate cross-cultural awareness.
Supportive social networks will then grow and foster both self-development
and increase cultural learning. These are the benefits for those who make
the best of their international assignments.
There are often other problems for families who relocate abroad, and then
move back to their original base, since 'repatriation' is not always easy.
Expatriates, who were known historically as 'exiles,' return to find that
they have missed significant developments in the lives of friends and
family. Having not shared in these events, former expatriates often report a
feeling of dislocation from the lives of their old friends.
Not everyone will make a success of relocation, so it is worthwhile making
early evaluations and preparation. We are talking here of an individual's
qualities, rather than qualifications.
Many relocation agencies have developed an awareness that husbands and wives
are not always 'on the same wavelength' about an intended move. According to
Carla Roundell-Greene of People and Property, it is important to understand
the social implications of moving to particular locations in order to
satisfy a particular housing need.
And how far can a prosperous, middle-aged couple with adolescent children
sustain initiatives to build social networks, when for a decade or more they
have enjoyed easy reciprocity with long-established friends and close
relations? Do they want to live within a corporate neighbourhood with
ready-made colleague/friends, - or as far from that as possible?
Providing realistic job/relocation previews is a wise course. Europeans
posted to busy and exotic locations - such as Hong Kong or Tokyo - have
sometimes suffered panic attacks in such densely populated and unfamiliar
urban environments.
Evaluating employees for likely success for an overseas posting can save a
lot of grief. Businesses with North American connections such as RHR
International - the firm of consulting psychologists - and PRlcoa Relocation
Management, a subsidiary of Prudential of America, which also offers
psychological advisory services, are aware of the legal and political
sensitivities of probing into employees' private lives. They offer the
family an opportunity to review their position within a confidential
counselling session, so that the family itself raises the crucial issues.
The outcome of this, according to Robert Brown, director of consulting at
PRlcoa, is that clear suitability may or may not be established, but the
particular training or support systems which will be needed to make a
success can be undertaken. As an aid to this, Brown uses a validated
psychometric instrument, the 'overseas assignment inventory.' He is careful
not to allow this to be used as a 'Go' - 'don't go' flag, but rather to help
the employee, the family and the employer see how a good judgment can be
made in complex circumstances.
Hambro Countrywide Relocation have now added a 24-hour 'stress counselling
service' to its relocation package for corporate clients. Occupational
psychologist Dr Tony Munton, a research fellow with the Medical Research
Council, says that 'people's attitude to the whole relocation operation in
influenced by the personal touch.
'However generous the financial package, the employee will not be grateful
unless he is helped to sort out the problems of new schools for children, a
job for the spouse and the possible pyschological fall-out from the stress
of the move.'
The writer is a consulting psychologist with RHR International.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-10589</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CD3BPADIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920430
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Survey of Relocation in The UK (6): The scientific approach
 -The Japanese manufacturer, Pioneer, applied rigorous economic criteria in
its search for a European production location
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DECISION by Pioneer Electronic, the hi-fi manufacturer, to invest Pounds
20m in a new factory at Wakefield, West Yorkshire, provides an insight into
the scientific approach to international industrial location.
A recent Institute of Directors survey in the UK found some companies
choosing a relocation site on the basis of golf club waiting lists and the
number of swans on a river: the Japanese approach is slightly different.
The story of Pioneer's move to Wakefield is one of careful strategic
planning providing the corporation's main board with a series of viable
options. But refreshingly the final choice may well have hinged on human and
cultural factors.
Pioneer wanted to be in Europe ahead of the 1992 Single European Market. In
many ways their investment in factories like Wakefield was risk capital
against the possibility that the EC would construct trade barriers around
'Fortress Europe.' Pioneer also wanted to expand in the midst of their
market.
For five years from the mid-1980s, Pioneer sent out an international study
team to look at European options. Enquiries to the UK for potential sites
would have been fielded by the Investment in Britain Bureau and the
Yorkshire and Humberside Development Agency. A second study team followed in
1989 to look at options in Yorkshire and Humberside and the UK's only other
continental rival: Barcelona.
Mr Zenkichi Igarashi, managing director of Pioneer Electronics Technology
(UK), explains the final choice: 'We chose Wakefield because of its
location, communications and workforce. If you draw a circle of a 300 km
radius around Wakefield, all our component suppliers in Scotland, Wales, and
the Midlands fall within that circle.
'Our Wakefield site is on the M62, half way between the interchanges with
the M1 and the A1, and so our suppliers can reach us in short time periods
and we can export our products through the Humber ports easily.
'The site is also adjacent to Port Wakefield and we hope to use the rail
freight terminal to export our finished goods through the Channel tunnel. We
also have good air links to Europe through Leeds/Bradford Airport and can
reach London in two hours by train.'
Wakefield's accessibility to suppliers appears to have been decisive as
Pioneer's goods must be 40 per cent value-added within the EC to count as
'Made in Europe.' The labour market factor also meant that Pioneer was
looking for a location away from competing Japanese inward investors:
Wakefield's hinterland has few competitors for Pioneer's light engineering
skills.
No financial inducements were offered to Pioneer to come to Wakefield, but
the role played by the metropolitan district council certainly helped force
Barcelona into second place. They provided an information answer-service for
Pioneer which always beat a 24-hour deadline.
Ms Amanda Spalding, acting deputy chief economic development officer, says
that on one occasion she rushed to Leeds with information on prevailing
winds at the Wakefield site and 'gatecrashed' a meeting of the Pioneer study
team. Interestingly, Japanese companies often require extensive written
submissions which are thoroughly double-checked - while US companies often
ask for condensed options.
Once inside the meeting, she had a unique glimpse of 'consensus'
decision-making as the team discussed, in Japanese, the various Yorkshire
and Humberside sites and then voted on various aspects of them: location,
workforce and so on. They then flew to Barcelona.
Having discovered that the group was staying in the Hotel Sofia (by faxing
all hotels of that name in the region]), Wakefield's team persisted in
providing prompt information faxed to Spain.
Once the final decision was made by the main board in Tokyo, it was swiftly
converted into a major investment with room for expansion. The Five Towns
Resource and Teaching Centre was made available for the project group. A
company was formed in May 1990, the building occupied (on a Green Belt site)
on June 3, 1991, and production began on August 12 1991.
In retrospect, the company admits that purely economic locational factors
were bolstered by cultural ones: English is Japan's second language and
clearly this factor also helped edge Barcelona from the field. An
Anglo-Japanese Saturday School has been set up in Leeds for the children of
relocated executives and managers and an Anglo-Japanese Society is being set
up with the help of the YHDA.
Of the 240 people working at the Wakefield site, only seven are from Japan:
two directors and five managers. All were offered relocation packages and
most brought their families with them to West Yorkshire. Next month the
workforce should jump a further 60 and the final target is 700.
Production thresholds have been met and the workforce has proved a success
with the new Japanese managers. Senior staff recruited in Yorkshire were
taken to Japan for two training courses. Communications have proved
excellent although the current public inquiry into the opening of Port
Wakefield, close to the Pioneer site, has thrown a shadow over links with
the Channel tunnel.
The only problem appears to be the factories' image of growth and
profitability which has focussed interest locally on the first round of wage
negotiations at the Wakefield plant where a single-union deal was struck
with the EETPU electricians union after a 'beauty contest,' including four
other unions. The company would point out that if low wages had been a
crucial location factor, they would have chosen Barcelona.
The recession has obviously tempered Wakefield's short-term potential for
expansion, but the site offers radical growth opportunities with just
100,000 square feet of production area on 30 acres. Production now includes
tuners, CD players, and mini-systems. Stereo radio tuners production was
relocated to Wakefield from Belgium.
Pioneer applied rigorous economic criteria to their search for a European
site tempered, when the choice was narrowed to two, by cultural and human
factors. The economist Losch said: 'The question of the best location is far
more dignified than determination of the actual one.' In Pioneer's case the
two were nearly identitcal.
</TEXT>
