<PROFILE>_AN-CD3BPADFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920430
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Survey of Relocation in The UK (5): Predicament of the
trailing partner - It can no longer be assumed that the wives of male
employees will automatically fall into line with relocating companies' plans
/ The issue of spouses' jobs is now more important
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KAREN DILLEY found herself as a 'trailing spouse'
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
the unattractive term used in the relocation business - when her husband
John recently had to move from the Midlands to the south-east coast for his
job.
A well-qualified secretary who had never been short of work back in Market
Harborough, she was shocked to find there was no job for her near her new
home in Hastings. She went from agency to agency for a month and then rang
her old employers. They said she could resume work on Monday morning and
that was enough to decide her. Mrs Dilley returned to Market Harborough
without her husband and went back to work.
The separation was not as serious as it might at first appear: Mr Dilley, a
trainer for Emap, the publishing group, had been posted to Hastings for just
six months and his company paid for him to travel back to Market Harborough
each weekend. Nevertheless, the strain on the couple was considerable -
surprisingly perhaps, the stress was worse for him than for her.
Mrs Dilley says she is 'one of the world's copers' and, unlike her husband,
was on her home territory, doing familiar work. Mr Dilley, meanwhile, was in
strange surroundings and, at the end of each busy week, was faced with a
long drive. His six-month stint has since been completed and they are now
re-united.
The predicament the Dilleys faced is increasingly common. The 'cornflake
family' of television advertisements - with a Dad who goes to work and Mum
who stays at home - is now comparatively rare. Women make up nearly 50 per
cent of the workforce and just 14 per cent of women fulfil the traditional
role of looking after their children full time. Few working couples can
afford to give up a chunk of the family income.
It can no longer be assumed, therefore, that the wives of male employees
will automatically fall into line with relocating companies' plans. Nor can
it be assumed that female employees will refuse to relocate because of their
husbands' jobs: the 'trailing' male is not the unusual figure he once was.
Organisations are aware of these trends. According to a survey carried out
by the Confederation of British Industry, 73 per cent of companies consider
that the issue of spouses' work has inhibited relocation plans; nearly half
agree that employees have refused to relocate because their partners would
have had to give up their jobs.
Mr Jim McCredie, from KPMG Management Consulting, says theissue of spouses
is now of such significance that relocation plans may be scuppered entirely
by the prospect of losing staff. One example he gives is of a semi-public
sector organisation - a quango - for which he carried out a relocation
feasibility study. The study showed the quango would have saved a great deal
of money by moving out of London and, operationally, the organisation would
have suffered little from the shift.
However, the study also revealed that up to 80 per cent of the staff might
have refused to move, chiefly because of their spouse's jobs. Says Mr
McCredie: 'For the money that was going to be saved, it was not worth the
risk they could lose so many people.'
The quango had a very high proportion of professional employees -
professionals are more likely than other groups to have professional
spouses, unwilling to ditch their careers.
According to Mr McCredie, seven or eight years ago the bulk of relocating
companies were organisations, like banks and insurance companies with high
numbers of clerical and administrative workers. These companies were
prepared, even keen, to lose employees because they could be hired more
cheaply at the new location.
In recent years, however, improved communications have meant that companies
staffed by professionals have formed a greater proportion of relocating
companies - the issue of spouses' jobs has therefore become of even greater
importance.
While the CBI survey found employers are aware of these trends, it also
highlighted the fact that few companies have formal policies for helping
spouses as part of their relocation packages. Just 9 per cent have formal
policies - of these, 30 per cent offer financial compensation and 70 per
cent give practical assistance such as career counselling, help with finding
a job and assistance with CVs.
A greater number of employers - more than 40 per cent - are prepared to
offer help to spouses informally, according to the CBI.
Again, practical help is the most popular, with 55 per cent providing job
search assistance, 33 per cent career counselling, and just 4 per cent
financial assistance.
According to Ms Sue Shortland, manager of the CBI's employee relocation
council, compensation for loss of earnings remains rare because it is seen
as too short-term a measure and no substitute for a spouse finding a job. In
the few companies where money is paid, it is likely to be equivalent to
three to six months of spouses' former salaries. Says Ms Shortland: 'More
common is help in identifying spouses' potential and converting skills.'
As far as the actual guarantee of a job is concerned, most organisations
will not want to get involved unless they themselves are also the employer
of the spouse. Marks and Spencer, for example, says it will always try and
provide suitable jobs for partners of relocating M and S staff - but only if
they already work for the company.
However, most organisations will want to stick to fairly basic practical
help, such as providing information packs about the new locality, so that
spouses can do their own research into local employment opportunities, says
Ms Celia Baxter of KPMG Management Consulting.
'Lots of companies don't want to get involved beyond providing a financial
package and trying to ensure a house-move that's as disruption-free as
possible. It's often cleaner for them not to make promises they can't
deliver later on,' she says.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
