<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Brazil set to approve coffee
relief package
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BILL HINCHBERGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A ROLL-over of Dollars 276m in debt and CrDollars 240b (Dollars 102m) in new
financing for the 1992-93 crop are the centrepieces of a government package
to boost the Brazilian coffee sector. The measures await approval by the
National Monetary Council, which is scheduled to meet today.
The length of debt refinancing will depend on the nature and source of the
original loan. For some, payments may be extended for up to five years.
New credit will be awarded on the basis of productivity and will favour
those who did not receive loans for the 1991-92 harvest. Growers who did not
receive credit last season and who produce fewer than 45 bags (60 kg each)
per hectare will have access to financing of CrDollars 11,000 per bag; those
whose production is between 45 and 90 bags will be able to borrow up to
CrDollars 13,000 per bag, and those who harvest more than 90 bags per
hectare can obtain funding of up to CrDollars 15,000 per bag.
Mr Suelly Evandro Amarante, president of the National Coffee Council (CNC),
a producers association, hailed the measures as 'highly positive' and 'an
important beginning' for a recuperation of the sector. However, he believes
the amount of new credit is insufficient. The CNC is also lobbying for
additional measures, including tax reductions and port reforms to ease
exports.
Mr Amarante stressed that domestic measures alone could not solve the
problems of Brazilian coffee producers.
</TEXT>
